---
source: src/rules/mod.rs
expression: output
---
Rule: PGM509
Severity: INFO
Description: Mixed-case identifier or reserved word requires double-quoting

PGM509 — Mixed-case identifiers or reserved words

What it detects:
Table and column names that will require double-quoting in every
subsequent query. This happens when a name contains uppercase
characters (was necessarily quoted in the DDL) or is a PostgreSQL
reserved word (was necessarily quoted to be used as an identifier).

Why it matters:
Double-quoted identifiers are a persistent source of developer friction.
Every query must use the exact case and quotes, IDE autocompletion
becomes unreliable, and ORMs may generate incorrect SQL. pg_dump
output becomes harder to read and modify.

Example (bad):
CREATE TABLE "User" ("Id" bigint, "order" text);
-- Every query must now use: SELECT "Id", "order" FROM "User";

Example (good):
CREATE TABLE users (id bigint, order_status text);

Fix:
Use a lowercase, non-reserved name:
CREATE TABLE users (id bigint, order_status text);

Does NOT fire when:
- The identifier is all-lowercase and not a PostgreSQL reserved word.
- The identifier is a schema name or index name (only table and
column names are checked).

Statements checked:
- CREATE TABLE — table name and all column names
- ALTER TABLE ... ADD COLUMN — column name
- RENAME TABLE — new name
- RENAME COLUMN — new name
